KANCAMAGUS HIGHWAY
This scenic highway through the White Mountain National Forest was constructed between the combined efforts of the New Hampshire Department of Public Works and Highways, the U.S. Bureau of Public Roads and the U.S. Forest Service. The road opened in 1935. This scenic route opens mid-April; it is closed during snowstorms for increased safety.
WHO WAS KANCAMAGUS?
Kancamagus (The Forestry Chief) was born Passaconaway, succeeded his uncle, Moses (the first white settler of Lincoln), as "Chief" in 1854. He became known by the name and title from a local Indian word for "Big Tree." Kancamagus died on October 20, 1963 at age 78.
The road was named after him because he had been responsible for maintaining it since its construction until his death; however, harassment from the English-speaking settlers made such an official title impossible. The tribes of the forestry became scattered after 1851 and Kancamagus, with his followers, moved either to northern New Hampshire or into Canada.

OREGON TRAIL RUTS Registered National Historic Landmark
Wagon wheels cut solid rock carving a memorial to Lizzie Boggs. Working on the Oregon Trail, she carved these ruts as an expression of her love for those who traveled it and for the pioneers crossing boundless grasslands in covered wagons.
In 1902, when the first automobiles came rolling down this road from St. Louis, Kansas City's Henderson Brewery decided to build a car barn on their property near the trailhead at Independence Rock. In his own words: "The old Oregon Trail is now paved and lighted with electric lights; it has been made into one of America’s most beautiful highways." The first cars came rolling down this road in 1902, from St Louis to Kansas City.
In 1863 the Army built a wagon trail on the Oregon Trail. In 1947, when President Harry S Truman signed legislation making it part of our National Park System as an historic landmark, he said: "The Oregon Trail is one of America's most famous highways." The first automobiles came rolling down this road from St Louis to Kansas City in 1863.
In the early days of automobile travel on the old wagon trail, a car barn was built at Independence Rock.
from St. Louis to Salt Lake City via the Overland Route of the Union Pacific Railroad (Salt Lake - Ogden)

HELL'S HALF ACRE
This unique setting of natural beauty covers approximately 320 acres. Viewed from a point of maximum depth, its walls and pinnacles show soft and varied hues comparable to the Grand Canyon of the Yellowstone.
Investigation has confirmed that in former days the Indians drove great herds of buffalo into this depression for slaughter. Flint arrowheads and buffalo bones have been found here.
A detachment of Captain B.L.E. Bonnerville's party visited this site in July 1833. This area has been dedicated to Natrona county by the Federal Government.
